Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday and welcome back to our 47th Weekly Dose of Optimism.
I don=E2=80=99t know if the world keeps producing optimistic stuff because =
it knows we need content for this weekly newsletter or if we just have a cl=
assic case of Baader-Meinhof on our hands. But either way, the world keep p=
roducing. And we=E2=80=99ll keep writing about it.
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
The Weekly Dose is brought to you by... Tegus [ https://substack.com/redire=
ct/a6f19f14-0c92-4548-9e65-f49396591f35?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Z=
lNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Spend your best time making bold investment decisions=E2=80=93 not hunting =
for elusive information. Tegus [ https://substack.com/redirect/a6f19f14-0c9=
2-4548-9e65-f49396591f35?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKb=
qOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] unites insights from credible experts with in-depth fina=
ncial data to give you fast, powerful perspectives.=C2=A0
Are you ready to go fast, build conviction, and outperform the market?=C2=
=A0
Unlock the power of Tegus with a free trial [ https://substack.com/redirect=
/a6f19f14-0c92-4548-9e65-f49396591f35?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlN=
uaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
(1) IBM quantum computer passes calculation milestone [ https://substack.co=
m/redirect/886cbcef-662f-49c3-b5d4-de2c213b6bf8?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J=
5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Davide Castelvecchi [ https://substack.com/redirect/29d3e380-16f7-4de4-9daf=
-fb60303c6439?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Ex=
kRNpU ] for Nature
Four years ago, physicists at Google claimed their quantum computer could o=
utperform classical machines =E2=80=94 although only at a niche calculation=
 with no practical applications. Now their counterparts at IBM say they hav=
e evidence that quantum computers will soon beat ordinary ones at useful ta=
sks, such as calculating properties of materials or the interactions of ele=
mentary particles.
In a proof-of-principle experiment described in Nature on 14 June1 [ https:=
//substack.com/redirect/79d82cb6-d06a-4074-9775-a433d03be98a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOX=
AwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], the researchers sim=
ulated the behaviour of a magnetic material on IBM=E2=80=99s Eagle quantum =
processor. Crucially, they managed to work around quantum noise =E2=80=94 t=
he main obstacle for this technology [ https://substack.com/redirect/0cabbe=
59-2706-4be4-833d-7725a0479134?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjml=
XXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] because it introduces errors in calculations =E2=
=80=94 to get reliable results.
What if I told you that IBM was well-positioned for the next major technolo=
gy wave?
You=E2=80=99d probably laugh me off with some quip about Watson. Which is f=
air =E2=80=94 IBM was early to AI and majorly dropped the ball, at least fr=
om a commercialization standpoint.
But we=E2=80=99re not talking about Watson. We=E2=80=99re not even talking =
about AI. We=E2=80=99re talking about quantum computing.
Quantum computing, a type of computation that utilizes quantum mechanics pr=
inciples like superposition and entanglement to perform complex calculation=
s at speeds that are significantly faster than traditional computing, holds=
 promise for advancing fields such as AI, cryptography, optimization, simul=
ation, and drug discovery.=20
Quantum computers have the potential to outperform classical supercomputers=
 exponentially, but the prevalence of 'quantum noise' leads to high error r=
ates, currently limiting their practical applications. So much of recent qu=
antum computing research is dedicated to reducing this error rate.
In 2019, Google came out and claimed their quantum computer could outperfor=
m classical machines =E2=80=94 although only on niche calculations with no =
practical applications. Now IBM, say they have evidence that quantum comput=
ers will soon beat ordinary ones at useful tasks, such as calculating prope=
rties of materials or the interactions of elementary particles.
In a new paper [ https://substack.com/redirect/464eaa90-a68e-4227-ac1e-420c=
d4803de5?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU=
 ], IBM claims their =E2=80=9Cerror-mitigating techniques=E2=80=9D managed =
to work with quantum noise to produce reliable results. Essentially, becaus=
e each quantum calculation is both unreliable and really fast, they can re-=
run the calculation a bunch of times, amplifying the noise very precisely i=
n each calculation in order to extrapolate back to what noise-less results =
might have been.=20
In this case, per the NYT, [ https://substack.com/redirect/ceb85fc3-cbbf-42=
65-8ad7-680a1ce05f7b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa=
8-6m8ExkRNpU ] =E2=80=9CThey used a quantum processor with 127 qubits to si=
mulate the behavior of 127 atom-scale bar magnets =E2=80=94 tiny enough to =
be governed by the spooky rules of quantum mechanics =E2=80=94 in a magneti=
c field. That is a simple system known as the Ising model, which is often u=
sed to study magnetism. This problem is too complex for a precise answer to=
 be calculated even on the largest, fastest supercomputers.=E2=80=9D
It=E2=80=99s a demonstration of real =E2=80=9Cutility=E2=80=9D in quantum c=
omputing, another one of those fields that seems to perpetually sit years a=
way from usefulness. We=E2=80=99re not quantum physicists, and it remains t=
o be seen how long it is before scientists and engineers are routinely usin=
g quantum computers to do real things, but with Cruise roaming the streets =
of SF, Apple=E2=80=99s VisionPro announced, and now this IBM breakthrough, =
a lot of those =E2=80=9Calways decades away=E2=80=9D technologies sure seem=
 to be coming to fruition this year.
(2) The Great Convergence [ https://substack.com/redirect/8488940e-2ed2-4b0=
4-a107-c883f0bfd192?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8=
-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Branko Milanovic [ https://substack.com/redirect/75d06b80-f415-405e-8850-05=
b2a7d2f18d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRN=
pU ] for Foreign Affairs
But then, around 20 years ago, global inequality began to fall, largely tha=
nks to the economic rise of China, which until recently was the world=E2=80=
=99s most populous country. Global inequality reached its height on the Gin=
i index of 69.4 in 1988. It dropped to 60.1 in 2018, a level not seen since=
 the end of the nineteenth century.
Would you believe me if I told you that global inequality is at its lowest =
level in nearly 150 years?
If not, I wouldn=E2=80=99t blame you. After all, the headlines and social m=
ovements that fill those headlines would lead you to believe otherwise. Tru=
mpism. Brexit. The Yellow Vest Movement in France. Black Lives Matter. Occu=
py Wall Street. The Global Financial Crisis. The list goes on and on. All s=
tories =E2=80=94 at their core =E2=80=94 about inequality.
=E2=80=9CGlobal inequality,=E2=80=9D which refers to income disparity betwe=
en all citizens of the world at a given time, adjusted for the differences =
in prices between countries, is commonly measured by the Gini coefficient. =
0 =3D total equality and 100 =3D a single individual has all the wealth.=20
All of the stories above are at the level of the nation-state, where inequa=
lity is real and persistent. At to be sure, there is some level of nation-s=
tate interconnectedness. But if you zoom out to a global scale, the world i=
s growing more equal than it has been for over 100 years. The decrease in g=
lobal inequality over the past two decades is thanks, in large part, to the=
 economic rise of China.
The question is whether or not this downward trend can continue. China, now=
 the world=E2=80=99s second most populace country, has already made its den=
t. And there are questions as to whether or not India, currently the world=
=E2=80=99s most populace country, can achieve the same growth story that Ch=
ina did in the early 21st century.
Our obvious hope is yes =E2=80=94 and new technologies like quantum computi=
ng, AI, affordable and effective medicines =E2=80=94 will all play a role i=
n driving down the Gini coefficient over the coming decades.
(3) Not Boring Founders: Dylan Beynon, Mindbloom [ https://substack.com/red=
irect/d420476c-081a-469d-bb5a-a8eb26837056?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7Gn=
A_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Packy was joined on Not Boring Founders by Dylan Beynon, the founder and CE=
O of Mindbloom [ https://substack.com/redirect/04674be9-3f05-4d44-a404-24ae=
0ddc8db7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU=
 ]. Mindbloom=E2=80=99s mission is to transform lives today, to transform t=
he world tomorrow through psychedelic medicine. And it=E2=80=99s starting w=
ith ketamine therapy for patients with depression and anxiety.
Mindbloom=E2=80=99s traction is part of a larger wave of research, commerci=
alization, and general de-stigmatization currently happening in psychedelic=
s. And this movement is catching on for a good reason: psychedelics are now=
 a proven, effective therapeutic for a number of ailments.=20
 For example, Mindbloom=E2=80=99s particular protocol of ketamine therapy h=
as been proven to be 40% more effective in treating depression and anxiety =
than SSRIs, with immediate results and few (if any) side effects. More rese=
arch is certainly needed, but the results are promising particularly for SS=
RI non-responders.
Packy talked with Dylan about why he started Mindbloom, how Ketamine therap=
y works, where the company and space are headed, and what the world looks l=
ike as access to psychedelic medicine expands.
(4) The US Factory Boom Is a Golden Opportunity for Green Job Training [ ht=
tps://substack.com/redirect/ca52e05a-ee53-4def-a529-c975dbeaacec?j=3DeyJ1Ij=
oiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] =F0=9F=94=92
Nathaniel Bullard [ https://substack.com/redirect/2cffd2c2-344f-4f92-934b-8=
27ce97d6c57?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ] for Bloomberg
Thanks to a combination of the Inflation Reduction Act [ https://substack.c=
om/redirect/0bc36121-15aa-45b9-ad72-650169f1a21d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8=
J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], the CHIPS Act=C2=A0and a genera=
l interest in re-shoring US capacity, manufacturers=E2=80=99 construction s=
pending=C2=A0has reached an annual rate of $190 billion [ https://substack.=
com/redirect/0ee2506e-4e8e-4700-8081-a12d3be8f2fd?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb=
8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. That is double the rate of jus=
t a year ago. Manufacturing as a share of US private-sector construction ha=
s not been this high since at least 1990, when government data sets begin.
IT=E2=80=99S TIME TO BUILD FOR THE BUILDERS. The U.S., in a coldish war wit=
h China, is racing to build up its manufacturing capacity and is spending h=
undreds of billions of dollars to do so. In fact, manufacturers constructio=
n spending has more than doubled year of year to both meet current demand a=
nd satisfy anticipated future demand for for things like semiconductors, el=
ectric vehicles, batteries, and solar panels.
And with all that money sloshing around, opportunity is plentiful. It=E2=80=
=99s a great time to be an engineer or an builder of climate friendly infra=
structure, or real any high-skilled worker. And of course, with that type o=
f money moving around, it=E2=80=99s a great time to be a middleman (consult=
ant, certifier, etc.)  sitting between government money and all those proje=
cts.
At any rate, America is making a strong push at re-establishing itself as a=
 manufacturing hub, at least for the products we deem important. That=E2=80=
=99s a good thing =E2=80=94 it builds up the middle class and reduces our f=
ragility and dependency.=20
(5) Bio x Hackathon Winner [ https://substack.com/redirect/602f4066-c83f-49=
70-aab9-1c05f9806eb9?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa=
8-6m8ExkRNpU ]: SVM
Elliot here. There's a renaissance happening right now at the intersection =
of AI and biology. It's like the fields are designed for each other=E2=80=
=94technologies like high-throughput DNA sequencing are creating massive an=
d complex datasets that take full advantage of the powerful AI models being=
 created.=20
Recently, our friends at Lux [ https://substack.com/redirect/d1593a25-3d29-=
4d25-8a00-15daab69e6ac?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqO=
sa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], Huggingface [ https://substack.com/redirect/d6cddc19-dcc9=
-4435-9952-1b7a8485ee21?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbq=
Osa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], Latch [ https://substack.com/redirect/db600526-1eca-4954=
-9d4a-ffcd04c13917?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-=
6m8ExkRNpU ], and OpenBioML [ https://substack.com/redirect/7a97b8d7-51bf-4=
249-aeb7-9c0ddc02a240?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOs=
a8-6m8ExkRNpU ] teamed up to host the Bio x Hackathon [ https://substack.co=
m/redirect/602f4066-c83f-4970-aab9-1c05f9806eb9?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J=
5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=E2=80=94where teams were given co=
mpute resources and a week to build a demo solving a useful problem in comp=
utational biology. The creativity and quality of the demos delivered on suc=
h a short time scale was amazing to see.=20
If you want to dip your toes into the world of computational biology, check=
 out this demo video from Erinc Merdivan [ https://substack.com/redirect/7f=
e47220-5442-462c-9dc4-119e7beddbc0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaM=
ZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]'s team that came in first place. Creating a pr=
ototype of unified protein embeddings in a week of work... what a time to b=
e alive.
Bonus: Varda Successfully Launches
On Monday, we wrote about  [ https://substack.com/redirect/95bec477-8d7f-47=
48-a942-9bb92c0f9921?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa=
8-6m8ExkRNpU ]Varda [ https://substack.com/redirect/95bec477-8d7f-4748-a942=
-9bb92c0f9921?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Ex=
kRNpU ], the company that=E2=80=99s manufacturing drugs in space for use on=
 earth to expand the economic bounds of humankind. Later that afternoon, Va=
rda=E2=80=99s spacecraft went up on SpaceX=E2=80=99s Transporter-8 rocket a=
nd successfully deployed. There is now a drug factory orbiting our planet.=
=20
Just yesterday, Varda confirmed [ https://substack.com/redirect/646132f6-a6=
a2-4779-9915-07dfb82b1e7b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepK=
bqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] that it=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cready to do some manufacturi=
ng without one of the four fundamental forces of physics.=E2=80=9D
From here, Varda=E2=80=99s spacecraft will orbit the earth for about a mont=
h before making its crucial re-entry and landing in the Utah desert. We=E2=
=80=99ll keep you posted.=20
Varda is easy to root for. It combines all of the things we love here at No=
t Boring. Hard problems. Declining cost curves. Flywheels. Biotech and spac=
e. And, of course, ambitious founders that are just crazy enough to launch =
a drug factory into space.=20
That=E2=80=99s all for this week. We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Tu=
esday. Enjoy the weekend!
Thanks for reading,
-Dan +Packy

