=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;=
">What if I told you that IBM was well-positioned for the next major techno=
logy wave?</p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26p=
x; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">You&#8217;d probably laugh me off with some quip ab=
out Watson. Which is fair &#8212; IBM was early to AI and majorly dropped t=
he ball, at least from a commercialization standpoint.</p><p style=3D"color=
: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>B=
ut we&#8217;re not talking about Watson. We&#8217;re not even talking about=
 AI. We&#8217;re talking about </span><strong>quantum computing.</strong></=
p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0=
 0 20px 0;">Quantum computing, a type of computation that utilizes quantum =
mechanics principles like superposition and entanglement to perform complex=
 calculations at speeds that are significantly faster than traditional comp=
uting, holds promise for advancing fields such as AI, cryptography, optimiz=
ation, simulation, and drug discovery. </p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font=
-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Quantum computers have=
 the potential to outperform classical supercomputers exponentially, but th=
e prevalence of 'quantum noise' leads to high error rates, currently limiti=
ng their practical applications. So much of recent quantum computing resear=
ch is dedicated to reducing this error rate.</p><p style=3D"color: #404040;=
 font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">In 2019, Google c=
ame out and claimed their quantum computer could outperform classical machi=
nes &#8212; although only on niche calculations with no practical applicati=
ons. Now IBM, say they have evidence that quantum computers will soon beat =
ordinary ones at useful tasks, such as calculating properties of materials =
or the interactions of elementary particles.</p><p style=3D"color: #404040;=
 font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>In a </span=
><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/464eaa90-a68e-4227-ac1e-420cd4803=
de5?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel=
 style=3D"color: #404040; text-decoration: underline;">new paper</a><span>,=
 IBM claims their &#8220;error-mitigating techniques&#8221; managed to work=
 </span><em>with</em><span> quantum noise to produce reliable results. Esse=
ntially, because each quantum calculation is both unreliable and really fas=
t, they can re-run the calculation a bunch of times, amplifying the noise v=
ery precisely in each calculation in order to extrapolate back to what nois=
e-less results might have been. </span></p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font=
-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>In this case, </=
span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/ceb85fc3-cbbf-4265-8ad7-680a1=
ce05f7b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU"=
 rel style=3D"color: #404040; text-decoration: underline;">per the NYT,</a>=
<span> &#8220;They used a quantum processor with 127 qubits to simulate the=
 behavior of 127 atom-scale bar magnets &#8212; tiny enough to be governed =
by the spooky rules of quantum mechanics &#8212; in a magnetic field. That =
is a simple system known as the Ising model, which is often used to study m=
agnetism. This problem is too complex for a precise answer to be calculated=
 even on the largest, fastest supercomputers.&#8221;</span></p><p style=3D"=
color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">It=
&#8217;s a demonstration of real &#8220;utility&#8221; in quantum computing=
, another one of those fields that seems to perpetually sit years away from=
 usefulness. We&#8217;re not quantum physicists, and it remains to be seen =
how long it is before scientists and engineers are routinely using quantum =
computers to do real things, but with Cruise roaming the streets of SF, App=
le&#8217;s VisionPro announced, and now this IBM breakthrough, a lot of tho=
se &#8220;always decades away&#8221; technologies sure seem to be coming to=
 fruition this year.</p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-h=
eight: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>(2) </span><strong><a href=3D"https=
